\begin_layout Subsection
Fundamental mechanisms when demand increases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Initial shock changes one or more demand components
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A positive demand shock is a shock that increases domestic demand for given
 prices.
 The demand curve shifts right.
 This occurs through changes in private consumption, public consumption,
 investments, exports or imports.
 The shock can be direct as with a shock to government consumption, but it is
 often indirect as with shocks to the income tax which change household
 income.
 Irrespective, the way the different demand shocks propagate through the
 model economy is similar and we discuss it in this section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased demand leads to increased sector production
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When demand increases, production from different sectors will increase via
 the input / output system.
 For given output prices and unit costs firms will want to meet the increased
 demand in order to increase profits.
\end_layout 

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased sectoral production leads to increased production inputs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to increase production, firms need to increase their capacity utilizati
on and/or their input of intermediates, labor and capital.
 Firms invest in capital based on their expectations for production in the
 coming periods.
 In the short and medium run, there is decreasing returns to scale due to
 installation costs, while in the long run there is constant returns to
 scale.
 Capacity utilization means that production in the short run is not only
 affected by the amount of production inputs used.
 In this manner, production in the individual sectors can increase more
 than factor input in the short term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Time-to-build and installation costs on capital mean that user costs on
 capital increase in the short run relative to other inputs and the K/L
 ratios in the individual sectors decrease.
 In the short run, it is thus easier to increase factor input from labor
 and intermediates compared to capital.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased intermediate inputs leads to increased imports and domestic sectoral
 output
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increased demand for intermediates results in increased demand for goods
 and services from other sectors and from imports.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased capital demand leads to increased investments from imports and
 domestic sectoral output 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increased investment also results in increased demand for production from
 domestic sectors and imports that deliver inputs to investment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased labor demand leads to increased wages, employment and labor supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The labor market takes the form of a search-labor market, where the wage
 is determined by annual negotiations for a share of the wage contracts.
 In order to increase employment, firms need to hire more employees and
 post more vacancies.
 The more vacancies that are posted in relation to the number of job seekers,
 the more difficult it is to get a match by a vacancy posting.
 The marginal cost of hiring thus increases for firms.
 In return, it becomes easier for the job seekers to get a match.
 The expected marginal gain from applying for a job increases, causing household
s to increase the effective labor supply.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increased marginal cost of hiring causes the marginal cost of labor to increase.
 It provides a larger wedge between the marginal cost of new employees that
 the firm is willing to pay and the salary that existing employees receive.
 This increases the bargaining power of existing employees, which puts upward
 pressure on salaries.
 Wages adapt sluggishly and make an additional gradual contribution to increasin
g the marginal cost of labor.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased employment and wages leads to higher household income and increased
 demand for private consumption and housing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increased employment and wages increase household income.
 The forward-looking households spread consumption out throughout their
 life and save something for inheritance taking into account the relative
 prices and expectations of future wealth and income.
 Habit consumption provides a more gradual adjustment, and benefit of wealth
 incl.
 to inheritance ensures that they save when old and do not borrow too much
 when young.
 The credit constrained households (so-called hand-to-mouth households)
 consume the entire income increase.
 Both types of households will, all other things being equal, increase consumpti
on when income rises, but the effect is strongest for credit constrained
 households in the short run.
 Furthermore, the effect for the forward-looking agents will depend on which
 age groups experience the income increase, as younger age groups in MAKRO
 have a higher marginal propensity to consume.
 The increase in private consumption reflects both an increase in consumption
 excluding housing and housing consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased housing demand leads to increased housing prices and investments
 in housing 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
 The increased housing demand results primarily in higher prices because
 the supply of housing changes slowly.
 The marginal price for increasing the housing volume is very high in the
 short run primarily because houses embody land which exists in rigid supply,
 and land and other inputs are not strong substitutes in the production
 of the final housing good.
 The housing volume thus only changes slightly in the short run, while the
 house price is quite volatile.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased housing prices leads to increased liquidity and demand for private
 consumption and housing 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Higher housing prices lead to a redistribution of wealth from those who
 purchase houses to those who sell.
 In isolation, this prompts a negative effect on private consumption, as
 home buyers in MAKRO (typically younger households) have a higher marginal
 propensity to consume than home sellers (typically older households) do.
 However, this effect is dominated by the fact that all households can borrow
 through a mortgage.
 Overall, this mechanism means that increased housing prices lead to a higher
 propensity to consume.
 There is thus an amplifying effect on consumption through demand shocks
 via increased loan financing in the housing market - a so-called financial
 accelerator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased production leads to a gradual increase in output prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increasing marginal vacancy posting costs and capital installation costs
 mean that firms’ unit costs rise in the short run.
 The firm has an additional way of increasing output in the short run, which
 is to increase its factor utilization, but increased capacity utilization
 today must be compensated for in the future.
 Overall, firms' unit costs are rising, eroding its margins and putting
 upward pressure on output prices.
 However, the increase in prices is gradual due to price setting rigidity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Higher output prices leads to higher demand prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The input / output system mechanically links higher output prices to higher
 demand prices based on input shares.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased prices dampens the quantity demand over time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increased prices reduce the quantity demand.
 In the product market for goods and services, the increased prices mean
 lower demand.
 For intermediates, the effect is modest, as the substitution elasticities are
 typically small.
 Investments are also generally not very sensitive to changes in investment
 prices and react more as a consequence of lower production due to the fall
 in other demand components.
 Private consumption reacts - primarily as a reaction to the fall in real
 income.
 Much more sensitive to changing prices are exports.
 The reaction is only gradual, but in the long run exports will change significa
ntly due to changes in relative prices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition, domestic demand is significantly affected by rising prices
 through the effect of relative prices on import content.
 Thus, the demand for domestic production of intermediates or private consumption
 will fall, even though the general demand for these components is only
 to a lesser extent affected by rising prices.
 As with exports, this reaction to relative prices is gradual.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Full crowding out in employment for permanent demand shocks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A permanent exogenous increase in domestic demand will over time result
 in crowding-out via foreign trade, improved terms of trade and higher real
 wages.
 In the short run, price and wage rigidities will create an increase in
 employment.
 In the long run, however, structural employment will be re-established.
 Higher domestic demand pushes up domestic prices and reduces exports.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Wages will typically grow more than domestic output prices, so that product
 real wages will grow.
 This is because the user cost of capital in the long run mainly depends
 on the investment price.
 Due to the high import content of the investments, these investment prices
 will grow less than the sectors’ output prices.
 This causes product-real-user cost to fall.
 In the long-run equilibrium, this will mean that real product wages grow
 and that there will be a substitution towards capital.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newpage newpage\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fundamental mechanisms when supply increases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased supply decrease prices for given demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A positive supply shock decreases prices for any given quantity produced.
 The supply curve shifts right.
 There is typically an effect via the production costs of the firm as with
 increased labor supply (lowers costs of labor), increased productivity
 (lowers effective costs of one or more production inputs), lower financial
 costs (lower capital costs) or lower foreign prices (lower intermediate
 input or investment costs).
 With output prices being set as a markup over costs, these prices also fall.
 Shocks to foreign prices also affect the demand prices directly through
 imports.
 Furthermore shocks to foreign prices affect demand through the import shares
 and exports both affected by foreign prices.
 Financial shocks is also most often more than a pure shock to financial
 costs and an interest rate shock will for example change the income flow,
 wealth and hence demand of the households.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we focus on labor supply and productivity shocks.
 Shocks to foreign prices and financial shocks are described in later sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased supply leads to fewer production inputs for given production and
 lower unit costs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A productivity shock lowers unit costs of production and inputs of labor,
 capital and materials are all reduced for a given production.
 Input of the more productive input is reduced as it is possible to produce
 the same with less input and this is not dominated by substitution effect
 as all substitution elasticities in the production is less than one.
 Input of the other factors are reduced due to substitution as the more
 productive factor has become cheaper in effective units.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Total labor input consists of workers times hours worked times individual
 productivity.
 Hours worked depend on taxes, wages and preferences and we can shock both
 preferences and taxes.
 Other preferences dictate search behaviour.
 Reducing the disutility of search will in increase the number of matches
 per vacancy posted by the firms and will decrease the marginal costs of
 hiring and hence the unit cost of firms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Lower unit costs leads to lower output prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lower unit costs cause the firms to lower prices.
 The increase is gradual due to rigidity, which makes it costly for firms
 to change the price sharply in the short term.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Lower output prices leads to lower demand prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The input / output system mechanically links lower output prices to lower
 demand prices based on input shares.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Lower prices increases quantity demand over time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lower prices increase the quantity demand.
 This is as described in the subsection 'Increased demand prices dampens
 demand over time primarily through 'foreign trade'' - but with the reversed
 sign.
 The effects from higher demand are described in the section 'Fundamental
 mechanisms when demand increases'.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Full crowding out in the unemployment rate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some permanent supply shocks can change the structural rate of unemployment,
 but most shocks do not and none of the above mentioned do.
 Increased demand will over time increase employment until the structural
 unemployment rate is unchanged.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If public consumption or foreign demand are exogenous, an increase in hours
 or participation will make domestic prices and real wages fall.
 The reason is similar to the mechanism described under the demand shocks.
 The larger labor supply will in the long run result in more domestic goods
 being produced.
 Domestic prices must fall to sell more goods in the export market.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased supply will over time cause scale effects in exports
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MAKRO has a scale effect in exports as long-term growth in private structural
 gross value added (GVA) leads to a corresponding growth in exports over
 time.
 One would typically think of such supply effects as something that materializes
 on an extensive margin: Exports of new product types or to new markets.
 In other Danish macroeconomic models (eg DREAM, SMEC or MONA), there is
 typically a significant effect on real wages in the event of a shock to
 labor supply.
 This effect is smaller in MAKRO due to the scale effect in exports.
