\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
A brief note on the sectors in in MAKRO
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are 9 sectors in MAKRO.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This compares with the 12 sectors in ADAM.
 Construction, sea transport, agriculture, extraction and housing are identical.
 The energy sector in MAKRO is the sum of the energy sector and the refinery
 sector in ADAM, while the manufacturing sector is the sum of the food sector
 and diverse manufacturing in ADAM.
 Finally, the public sector in ADAM is equal to public administration and
 services, while the private industry is financial services, other private
 services and public services minus public administration and services.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
 Some of the sectors are less central to shock analysis than others due
 to several factors.
 For example, the housing sector is driven solely by household demand, and
 draws almost exclusively from the construction sector.
 The extraction industry is exogenously given and production is thus not
 affected by shocks.
 Maritime transport (shipping) and agriculture are small industries with
 a limited share of both GVA and employment, which means that their role
 is limited when describing the aggregate effects of shocks.
 This is especially true for maritime transport, where it is also the case
 that exports - due to high import content - are largely independent of
 Danish prices.
 The energy sector is interesting when energy taxes change, while it does
 not play a major role in many other shocks.
 Although the public sector is large, it is exogenous and therefore only
 important if it is shocked directly.
 The two main sectors are therefore (private) services and manufacturing.
 Services are important by virtue of their size: they account for almost
 half of GVA and over half of employment as well as approximately one third
 of aggregate investment.
 The manufacturing sector is smaller, but it is still significant in terms
 of describing the response to various shocks.
 This is because the manufacturing sector is the largest supplier to exports,
 just as the majority of imports are from foreign manufacturing industries
 that substitute for domestic manufacturing.
\end_layout

