Sector prices and taxes determine the prices of the demand components.
 As a general rule, the input structure is exogenous, independent of relative
 prices, and changes only to a limited extent over time.
 For unchanged taxes, table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Brancherne-i-MAKRO-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 gives an overview of which sectoral output prices affect the prices of
 materials, private consumption, public consumption, investment and exports
 respectively.
 In general, intermediate input prices are mostly affected by services,
 imports and manufacturing.
 The price of private consumption excl.
 housing is primarily affected by services and imports.
 The housing deflator - used in the empirical calculation of total private
 consumption - is determined on the basis of imputed regulated rents and
 is generally not affected by shocks.
 The deflator for public consumption is determined primarily on the basis
 of the output price of public production.
 The investment price of machinery capital is determined primarily on the
 basis of the prices of services, manufacturing and imports, while the price
 of building investments is primarily determined on the basis of the price
 of construction and services.
 The price of the construction sector is in isolation important for the
 investment price of buildings, but this price is in isolation not so important
 for the rest of the economy, as buildings only make up a small part of
 firm costs, and user costs in the short run primarily reflect installation
 costs.
 Export prices are primarily affected by prices for manufacturing, services
 and maritime shipping.
 However, as the price of shipping is almost not affected by domestic conditions
, this is not so important for the volume of exports for most shocks.
